Good deal.  You should like the 125.  I&#39;ve noticed the sweep on the AM is just slightly slower than the 469, but I&#39;ve gotten the best communication with the 125.

Speakjet is an IC chip that will produce speech with the use of allophones.  The idea is that you&#39;d ask questions like you would with the radio and a spirit makes use of the allophones to generate words.  The allophones act as the raw audio instead of radio snippets.  Someone in the group, can&#39;t remember who, brought this to our attention.  

Stefan Bion has taken the idea of allophones and incorporated it into his software program EVPMaker. Some here have gotten great results using this method.

Jeremy


----- Original Message ----
From: lunalamia &lt;rainspirit1@...&gt;
To: EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com
Sent: Sunday, April 6, 2008 3:18:53 AM
Subject: [EVP-ITC] Re: Difference between new 12-470 and old one? ~ Jeremy

                Jeremy ~ Yes, I just hacked a 20-125 last night and will be trying it 
out tomorrow when I have the time to actually sit down and do it and 
am not too tired. I agree...frame of mind is definitely important.

I have only done the regular evp with a digital voice rec.
I would LOVE to own an actual box someday, but am happy to have this 
for now.
What&#39;s a speakjet?

~ Laura

--- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups .com, Early Cuyler &lt;ecuyler@... &gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;ve got the 20-125 and an older 12-469 sans speaker and clicking.  
The 20-125 works wonderfully and has produced great results.  The 12-
469 has produced great results also.  Bruce can testify to the 
communication he gets with the 20-125.  
&gt; 
&gt; In the end, it all depends on signal strength and our spirit 
friends capability to communicate, not to mention our state of mind 
when we conduct a session.  There are a lot of variables involved, so 
there really is no one box better than the others in my opinion.  
Although, Frank seems to get some tremendous results with his 
creations.
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m actually going to attempt a Speakjet box.  I hope I can get 
past my semi-electronic retardedness and make it work.  
&gt; 
&gt; Jeremy




